commText: Four long years, and not much has changed. Chepauk remains a fortress for CSK and Dhoni remains its main attraction in front of adoring crowds who went berserk after those back-to-back sixes from their captain today. And of course, spin continues to hold sway here, though as Dhoni said, this pitch was much better to bat on. So that's it from us for now. Hope you enjoyed our coverage. This is Sagar Chawla signing off on behalf of Saurabh Shankar, Abhinand Raghavendran, Siva and Harish. Goodnight!

commText: B0$ Terrific high-scoring game. All of us were thinking how the wicket would be. It was the perfect first game that could happen. I thought it would be much slower. But it was a wicket where you could score runs. I was quite surprised with the wicket. But we'll have to see if we can produce a wicket like this game after game. commText: B0$ It was a pretty good wicket to bat on. Both powerplays looked challenging for the bowlers. Our job was to try and tie it up a little bit through the middle. It's always nice when Moeen takes a couple of wickets. On this wicket, it makes it easier with the boundary dimensions. I'm kinda used to that playing in New Zealand, we tend to play on one side of the block. It's a privilege to play any game, so I try to do my best. The wicket was a bit flatter than I wanted it. The last time we were here, it was spinning every game. Maybe as the tournament goes on, we might play a couple more spinners. It was awesome (to be back), had fond memories back in 2019. Nice to play in front of all these people tonight, they make it pretty loud. Sea of yellow, it's a privilege to play in front of them.

B0$ Not the ideal start after winning the toss. The first couple of overs it was a bit sticky and there was a bit of movement, but we did not bowl in the right areas and they got that flier. When you have quality batters in the opposition, they make you pay. Something for us to learn but the way Rutu and Conway played was brilliant. It does take time to learn what lengths to bowl on a surface, but to go for 70 odd in six overs isn’t ideal. We batted well but we didn’t capitalize the small momentum. Kyle (Mayers) is coming off good form, he was smoking them for West Indies and comes here with the same form and intent. Great to see what he’s done with the opportunity. Bishnoi is someone I’ve played with for a while, he gets wickets when things aren’t going well, puts his hand up and contains runs. Good to see different guys putting their hands up. Wouldn’t change the toss decision, we didn’t win because we didn’t capitalize the small moments. We had a good start but couldn’t press on. Not often we’ll find 4-5 guys caught on the boundary ropes, they needed to go over and will go over the next time. We’ll take that in T20 cricket, today the game didn’t go our way but this is the way we want to keep playing.

It was again an extraordinary display of powerhitting from him, bringing up fifty off just 21 balls and getting LSG off to a flier. But the game turned around as soon as spin was brought on, with Moeen Ali bowling a superb spell, and Santner doing a brilliant job as well. That was just classic CSK in action at their fortress, with Dhoni pulling the right strings. LSG were 73/0 after the first 5 overs. But they had collapsed to 136/5 after 14, with Moeen picking up a wicket in each of his four overs. The turnaround was made all the more sweeter by Deshpande who overcame a poor start with the ball to execute some good plans at the death, getting rid of Nicholas Pooran in the process and putting the final nail in LSG's coffin.

B0$ B1$ It’s been 1427 days since Chennai Super Kings have played at their revered AmbuDen. That’s a long time, long enough for the IPL to induct two new teams - one of whom will be their opponents today. Long enough for MS Dhoni to retire from International cricket and retire into a reclusive life, but still command the ability to sell-out stadiums in an instant with fans flocking by for a rare glimpse of their Thala. Long enough that some would have forgotten how much of a fortress Chepauk used to be for CSK - they’ve lost just 15 out of 56 games played at this venue.

Chennai Super Kings are home, and aren't they glad about it. The long wait and the eventual return is the theme for every team this season but MS Dhoni & Co. perhaps feel it stronger in their bones as they get back to a venue where they've won far more than they've lost since the inception of the tournament. 
 
Look no further than the last time they played at the venue (2019 season) to understand why it serves as the absolute definition of home advantage - six of CSK's nine league wins came there. So here they are again, in the quest to right the wrongs of last season and add some points table cushion for the road. 
 
Lucknow Super Giants are thus, the first ones this season to arrive with the baton to poke holes at statistical advantages like these. They come armed with an explosive top-order that ripped Delhi Capitals' attack to shreds on a true surface at home just two days ago. How well they can repeat those actions, possibly on a slower and stickier surface, will determine their ability to challenge CSK's home supremacy and even lay down a blueprint on how to play at Chepauk. 
 
In a venue where spinners have invariably snatched all the spotlight, these two teams - with at least two left-handers in their top-order - have intriguing mini-battles in store. CSK could have two left-arm spinners (Ravindra Jadeja and Mitchell Santner) while LSG are also equipped with at least one spinner (Ravi Bishnoi bowls more googlies than legspinners) who will turn the ball into the left handers. Which attack manages to pull off better damage-limitation could have a significant say in the direction the game takes.
